<TITLE> Suicide bombings kill 36 in Iraq, Baghdad hotel hit </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BAGHDAD, June 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A suicide bomber killed 10 people in the lobby of a busy Baghdad hotel used by foreigners and Iraqi officials, one of three separate attacks that killed a total of 36 on Monday, police and witnesses said. In the northern oil city of Baiji, 18 people were killed and another 40 wounded when a suicide bomber rammed a fuel tanker into protective walls outside a police headquarters. Police also said eight people died when a suicide car bomber struck outside the governor's office in the southern Shi'ite city of Hilla. In Baghdad, police said a bomber wearing a vest packed with explosives had walked into the busy lobby of the Mansour Hotel, where Sunni Arab tribal leaders from western Anbar province had gathered for a meeting. Iraqi state television said a prominent tribal leader was among the dead. "It was a huge explosion, the whole building shook for a few seconds," said one witness in the multi-storey hotel. The witness said the lobby had been badly damaged. Another witness said he had seen seven bodies, while police said 10 people had been killed and 15 wounded. Some Sunni tribal leaders in Anbar have joined forces to form U.S.-backed provincial police units to fight against Sunni Islamist al Qaeda, prompting a bloody power struggle in the vast desert region. U.S. and Iraqi officials blame most car bomb attacks in Iraq on Sunni Islamist al Qaeda. Monday's three big blasts came after a relative lull in the number of such attacks in the past week. A car bomb killed 87 people at a Shi'ite mosque in central Baghdad on June 19. Baiji police Captain Ghazwan al-Janabi said the bomber rammed a fuel tanker into high protective walls near the back of the police headquarters in the city, 180 km (110 miles) north of the capital. The attacks follow the launch of US-led offensives in beltways and provinces around Baghdad to deny al Qaeda militants sanctuary in farmlands and towns from where they launch car bomb attacks and other violen
